	II. A MORE DETAILED PROPOSAL
	
	
	CHAPTER 1 THE POLITICAL ECONOMY OF AN FTA 
		Thomas R. Donahue, Secretary-Treasurer of the AFL-CIO 
	told the Senate Finance Committee on February 6th, 1991: "The 
	enactment of a free trade agreement with Mexico, as proposed 
	by President Bush, would be an economic and social disaster 
	for U.S. workers and their communities, and do little to help 
	the vast majority of Mexican workers." 	A coalition of more 
	than 400 major corporations and trade association signed an 
	open letter strongly supporting a FTA. Congress is divided. 
	All of a sudden the proposed FTA has become a major domestic 
	policy issue in the United States.
		Mexican wage levels, lack of effective safety 
	standards and environmental safeguards in Mexico are raised by 
	opponents of an FTA. They argue that US firms will chose the 
	low wage option in preference to raising productivity and that 
	they woill flee from regulatory standards, leaving US workers 
	behind.  A coalition encompassing at least 20 different labor 
	and citizens-issues groups has organized to fight the FTA. The 
	proposed remedy of the labor coalition is to raise Mexican 
	wages and standards as part of an agreement.1 The issue is 
	placed in the broader context in which low-wage strategies of 
	producing in the third world are identified as a key 
	destructive force in the living standard of American workers.2 
	The coalition has paid virtually no attention (as labor has 
	always failed to do) to domestic adjustment programs. 
		The controversy surrounding the proposed FTA with 
	Mexico is misplaced. Free trade with Mexico cannot be a 
	panacea for all US problems, nor will it create "an economic 
	and social disaster for US workers and their communities" as 
	argued by the AFL-CIO.
		Any job losses are bad news at a time where real wages 
	are depressed and employment at best stagnant, but it must not 
	become an argument for stopping a good move in trade policy. 
	We accept and indeed applaud competition as the key driving 
