		The next step is to ask what would happen if Congress 
	decided in favor of an FTA with Mexico. In my judgment that 
	would mean a strong stabilization of the Mexican macroeconomy 
	-- more confidence that reforms would not be reversed, less 
	risk of a confidence crisis, capital flight and exchange rate 
	crises. With a gain in confidence part of Mexican flight 
	capital -- in my estimate between $60 and 100 billion are 
	parked offshore in Miami or Switzerland-- would return. 
	Availability of foreign exchange would allow the financing of 
	normal trade deficits. 
		Judging from the experience of developing countries 
	that do have financing I would expect a deficit in Mexican 
	trade of 2 percent of their GNP or $6-8 billion in the mid-
	90s. The shift from the current position to these deficits 
	would translate into at least an extra 150,000 jobs in the 
	United States.
		These numbers refer to net job creation in the US. In 
	some industries (apparel, cheap glass, parts) there would be 
	an increase in imports. In other industries including upper 
	level cars, chemicals, textiles there would be a major rise in 
	exports. Accordingly there will be some adjustment problem, 
	but we will gain good jobs and will lose some medium to poor 
	jobs. It is in this area that we need a major commitment to 
	retraining. 
		 Over time the market would solve the adjustment 
	problem but not in a way that is socially acceptable. For this 
	reason, I believe a successful FTA needs to have two 
	components to address this problem, First, a very substantial 
	phase-in period say 10 years or even 15 for industries 
	adversely impacted. For the phase-in period we can 
	differentiate across industries and thus implicitly lighten 
	substantially the adjustment problem. Second, there needs to 
	be a major commitment of attention and resources to retraining 
	and skill building.
	
